SIMPLE: dissonant
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dissonant
<hw>Dis"so*nant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>dissonans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>dissonare</ets>
to disagree in sound, be discordant; <ets>dis-</ets> + <ets>sonare</ets>
to sound: cf. F. <ets>dissonant</ets>. See <er>Sonant</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Sounding harshly; discordant; unharmonious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With clamor of voices <qex>dissonant</qex> and loud.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disagreeing; incongruous; discrepant, -- with
<xex>from</xex> or <xex>to</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Anything
<xex>dissonant</xex> to truth.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What can be <qex>dissonant</qex> from reason and nature than that
a man, naturally inclined to clemency, should show himself unkind and
inhuman?</q> <rj><qau>Hakewill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Disspirit</ent>⟦br⟧
